java.io.Serializable
public abstract class gc
extends jvr

Java encapsulation of the Dialogic GlobalCall Software (functions matching gc_*).

Since JVR uses the GlobalCall event functions within it's own event handling system, this class contains a static initialization block that forces the execution of Start(net.threebit.jvr.GC_START_STRUCT). Ergo, applications do not need to start the GlobalCall system manually. The static initialization is as follows: 

 static {
   gc.Start(null); // Starts all call control libraries.
 }

Method Detail

Start

public static int Start(GC_START_STRUCT start)
                 throws JVRException
gc_Start() starts the call control libraries. This method is called with a null argument automatically by JVR when the gc class is initialized. In other words: you never need to call this function. In fact, errors will occur if you try. Since null is passed in the default implementation there is no opportunity to pass in custom startup parameters. This will be dealt with in a future release.

CCLibStatusEx

public static int CCLibStatusEx(java.lang.String cclib_name,
                                GC_CCLIB_STATUSALL status)
                         throws JVRException
gc_CCLibStatusEx.

This method has two modes of operations:

  • cclib_name == "GC_ALL_LIB". In this mode, the supplied status object will be used to return the status of all of the Call Control Libraries.
  • Otherwise, the status parameter is ignored (supply NULL if need be) and the status of the specified Call Control library is provided by the method return value. This differs from the original Dialogic spec that requires an (int*) argument.

Dialogic API Reference for this function: (win32,linux)

gc_WaitCall.

Instead of taking a (CRN*) argument, when running in EV_SYNC mode, the call reference number will be returned. Otherwise, the return value is unmodified, except that it is a long instead of an int.
